    "description": "A comprehensive comparison between Next.js and Nuxt covering SSR, routing, deployment on edge networks, and developer experience.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "siliconbased.dev"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is Nuxt better than Next.js?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Neither is objectively 'better.' It depends primarily on your underlying framework preference (Vue vs React). Nuxt is often praised for a smoother developer experience and auto-imports, while Next.js boasts a significantly larger ecosystem and job market."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can Nuxt be deployed to Vercel like Next.js?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. Nuxt's Nitro server engine is specifically designed to run on a wide variety of hosting providers, including Vercel, Netlify, Cloudflare Pages, AWS, and traditional Node servers. It is not locked into a single ecosystem."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the Next.js App Router?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The App Router is a paradigm shift in Next.js introduced in version 13. It heavily utilizes React Server Components to execute rendering logic on the server, significantly reducing client-side JavaScript. It replaced the older 'Pages' router as the recommended approach."
        }
